Raw dev notes -- Automating the Brain: Daily Syncs and GitHub Actions Fun

Okay, so this RAG Knowledge Base Pipeline project is essentially my attempt to build a smart, queryable brain for a specific domain. It pulls in information from various sources, processes it, and makes it available for me to ask questions against. The whole point is to keep this "brain" fresh and up-to-date without me having to constantly babysit it.

This past week was all about making that automation a reality. The biggest win was getting the daily content sync fully automated using GitHub Actions. Before, I had to manually kick off a script to pull in new posts and comments. Now, it just runs on a schedule, which is a huge relief. I also hooked up email notifications so I get a summary of what changed each day. I spent a good chunk of time refining those emails – initially, they were pretty barebones, but now they include direct URLs to the new content, who commented, and even which "mega-files" (my internal term for larger, aggregated content files) were affected. This makes the notifications actually useful for quickly scanning what's new.

There were a few classic developer struggles, too. The GitHub Actions persistence thing was a real head-scratcher for a bit. My `sync_new_content.py` script would run, generate an output file, but then in subsequent steps of the action, that file would just... vanish. It took some debugging to realize that the ephemeral nature of GitHub Actions runners meant I needed to explicitly "dual-write" the output to a specific `sync_output/` directory that was configured to persist across steps. Classic "works on my machine" vs. "works in CI" problem. Also, the eternal battle with line endings popped up – a quick `.gitattributes` addition and a normalization commit sorted that out, but it's always a minor annoyance. Finally, I did a small refactor to align the sync output layout with a specific internal pattern, which just makes things cleaner and more consistent.

Honestly, getting this daily sync fully automated feels like a massive weight off my shoulders. It's one of those "set it and forget it" features that really makes a project feel robust and mature. I learned a lot about the quirks of GitHub Actions, especially around how state and files are handled between steps. It's a good reminder that CI/CD isn't just for running tests; it's a powerful orchestration tool. The satisfaction of seeing those daily emails pop into my inbox, knowing the system is diligently updating itself without my intervention, is immense. It's a small step, but it feels like a big leap in making this project truly self-sustaining and reducing my cognitive load.

Next up, I want to explore more sophisticated content change detection.
